    {"topic":"Postmodernism","difficulty":"medium","question":"Lyotard's 'differend' describes a conflict where:","options":["Different cultures disagree","One party's wrong cannot be expressed in the other's idiom — no shared rule of judgment exists","Scientific and humanistic discourses conflict","Two arguments are equally valid"],"answer":1},
    {"topic":"Husserl","difficulty":"medium","question":"Husserl's 'transcendental idealism' holds that objects as experienced are constituted by:","options":["The empirical brain","Transcendental consciousness — the acts of consciousness constitute the sense (but not the existence) of objects","Language and culture","Social practice"],"answer":1},
    {"topic":"Foucault","difficulty":"medium","question":"In 'The Order of Things', Foucault's 'episteme' refers to:","options":["Individual knowledge","The underlying unconscious structure that determines what counts as knowledge in a given historical period","Scientific method","The sum of all knowledge in an era"],"answer":1},
    {"topic":"Existentialism","difficulty":"medium","question":"Heidegger's 'being-toward-death' means authentic existence requires:","options":["Fear of death","Acknowledging one's own death as the outermost, non-relational, certain possibility that individualizes Dasein","Denying mortality","Religious hope in afterlife"],"answer":1},
    {"topic":"Logical Positivism","difficulty":"medium","question":"Schlick argued that only the structural form of scientific knowledge is communicable because:","options":["Content is communicable","The content of experience cannot be transmitted — only form is inter-subjectively sharable","Forms are prior to content","Logical form determines content"],"answer":1},
    {"topic":"Linguistic Philosophy","difficulty":"medium","question":"Austin's illocutionary act is:","options":["The physical sounds made","The act performed in saying something (e.g., promising, warning, asserting)","The effect produced in the hearer","The conventional meaning of the words"],"answer":1},
    {"topic":"Heidegger","difficulty":"medium","question":"Heidegger's 'critique of technology' argues that modern technology reveals the world as:","options":["A collection of objects","Bestand — a 'standing reserve' to be ordered and optimized, concealing Being","Something to be contemplated aesthetically","Naturally given and independent"],"answer":1},
